segments.text: When he was reading, was it okay for his daughter to interrupt him?
Sure.
He never did cause me any kind of problems, any kind of discipline.
It was my mother.
Now, what were your mother's rules for you?
Well, just normal, normal behavior.
But my father never did.
What did she do for relaxation?
Did she have some clubs?
Yeah, she bombed some clubs.
What were they?
Well, they were ladies' social clubs, mainly.
Was it named the social club then?
No, let's see.
I've got to get my schools connected.
Because the ones I can remember now are mostly OU.
See, that's been since 1925 that she's been, that she was down in OU, so I don't remember the ones way back.
Did she, did she have a group of women that came every, did they meet weekly or monthly?
Well, if she belonged to one, it would be just monthly or something like that, I suppose.
I don't really know about that.
Did you all go to church off campus?
Mm-hmm.
Where?
We always went to church.
And they supported both churches.
I said one was a Methodist and one was a Baptist.
And we'd go to first one church and then the other church.
And they, as I said, supported both of them.
And I never did understand why they didn't combine them.
Then did they decide which church you would attend?
Well, I just went with them.
You went to both?
I just went with them.
Wherever they went, I went.
So I'm asking you, about to ask a leading question.
So did you grow up and become a Baptist or a Methodist?
I came up and joined my...
The Sunday that I got back from my honeymoon, I went down and joined my husband's church, First Christian Church.
First Christian, the disciples.
Yeah.
Did you see the church up here, the...
One looks like a beehive.
Well, that's our first Christian church.
Oh, okay.
And you should have heard my husband after he saw those plans.
The minister called him and asked him to come by and look at the plans when he came home.
He said, you wouldn't believe what I've just seen.
Oh, he was so put out and so mad about this.
Beehive, as he called it.
But it's really a very fine plant.
And they've got a theater room, a building.
And it's fine.
In your days at A&M, was there an organized Baptist church
And Methodist Church next to the campus?
No, but I noticed in this annual, in the organizations, it would be the Baptist group and the Methodist group of students.
They were organized on the campus, and I had forgotten about that.
Let's see, back to student life.
Where did the Aggie men get those beautiful boots in those days?
I don't know, but sure I had them.
They kept them polished.
Later there would be a couple of boot makers just across the north side of the campus.
They were not there then?
I don't know.
Were Aggie rings kind of sacred at that time?
Yeah, I guess they were.
I don't know about that.
Let's see.
Do you remember your dad ever complaining about the board of directors?
Did the board of directors try to sometimes interfere too much?
I don't remember whether they did or not.
He's not a politician in any sense of the word.
And when he got up here, he had some legislative problems getting his library building and some other things.
But I don't remember.
And ask in there about anybody that I remember.
And anybody I remember is mostly just by name now because it's been too long.
I can't remember.
And I know that one of the members of the board of directors when we were down there was Mr. F.M.
Law.
Does that name mean anything?
Yes, ma'am.
Law Hall is a cherished building on the campus.
How did...
How did your father and Mr. Lowell become acquainted?
Do you remember?
Well, I guess it was because he was, I don't know whether he was president of the board.
At one time he was.
Well, that's what I was thinking, but I was just assuming that because his name comes to my mind more than any of the rest of them.
Do you remember any of the governors during that period?
What about Governor Ferguson?
Sure.
I just remember Ma Ferguson.
I was wondering, did you meet Ma?
I don't remember that I ever did meet her.
Because I would like to know more about her.
She's apparently a very distinctive lady.
Did your dad spend much time going to and from Austin?
I don't remember about that either.
Probably had to go over there some.
But do you ever...
I'll run into the name Ike Ashburn.
Yes, ma'am.
Well, he was a real loved person on the campus in those years, and very popular.
He was a commandant of the Corps in this book right here.
And it had a very complimentary letter from
from somebody about the way the student body had been trained.
Do you describe Colonel Ashburn?
He was a big man, great big man, fine looking man.
Pleasant?
Very pleasant.
He married my mother's cousin from Navasota, Bula Cook.
They had a son, Ike Junior.
And then when they had a child later, she and the baby died during childbirth.
So that was a blow to everybody that knew Ike Ashburn.
Did Mr. Cashin get there before you all left to direct the YMCA?
I don't believe so.
DX Bible.
Oh, my father brought him down.
How did they link up?
Do you know?
I don't know, but he was a very favorite.
The D.X.
Bible was just a... What made him their favorite?
I don't know.
Because he was at Mississippi College before coming to A&M.
Yeah.
And then he brought with him a young man named Anderson.
I don't remember him.
who would be nicknamed Andy.
And he would become the great, great, great track coach and also the Commandant of the Corps.
Do you remember a football player named Hiney Weir?
The name, you know, that's a very familiar name.
Do you remember anything more?
No.
I can't remember.
The reason I'm
is because he is the football player who has the knee injury in the Texas game before they go to Dallas to play a postseason game in the Cotton Classic.
Oh, yeah.

And Coach Bible turns to young Ashburn, a young Anderson, and says, remember four years ago when we were at Mississippi College, we were playing Mississippi State, and for the first time in history we were ahead of them
But a bunch of our guys got hurt, and we didn't have enough players to have 11 men on the field all the time.
So you go up there in the bleachers and get King Gill, who is Hiney Weir's substitute, and he's here as a spectator, tell him to go put his uniform on because if we need him,
We'll want him to play today.
And that's where the 12th man legend got started.
And that's why I was wondering if you knew, remembered Honey Weir.
I certainly remember the name.
Coach Bible, describe him as you recall him.
Well, a very fine personality.
Everybody liked him, so far as I know.
I think he was very popular and a wonderful coach and everything.
I don't know of anything other than good things I could say about him.
Did athletes go to class then?
I suppose so.
Well, did students all go to class then?
Do you remember students playing around when classes were in session?
No.
I probably didn't know much about that.
When you were in class, did students go to sleep much in class?
I don't recall that they did.
Probably did.
Well, let's see, you said no fires and tornadoes and train wrecks.
We have had tornadoes, but we've been fortunate right here.
We had one in Nichols Hills just this spring.
And I remember reading about that one.
Yeah, but the big one, you know, was just in May.
That's when we had our big
to tore down everybody's houses in that very big area.
Compare being a student at A&M to being a student at the University of Texas.
It was more fun being a student at A&M, I can say.
Describe what made it more fun.
Well, I was just so much more gung-ho about A&M than I was Texas University.
And that is a shame to say, because I'm really proud of my degree from Texas University.
But it was just the nature of things for me to feel like I did about A&M.
The conduct of the two student bodies, was there any difference?
Well, it was totally different, not having any military, but the ones I was associated with were just very normal, very nice people.
Were Aggies more respectful to young ladies than Longhorns were?
I don't know that they were.
I had some things.
I don't know whether you care about it.
Did you show him the picture?
Well, when you were talking about World War I, I just handed it to him.
Yes, ma'am.
Oh, did you see this?
Yes, ma'am.
Oh, that's a special card.
Special card.
Your family had a telephone always when you all... Mm-hmm.
My phone number was 65.
Mm-hmm.
Where was the telegraph office?
Oh, I don't know about that.
Was there even one at College Station?
Oh, I imagine.
I don't know.
Do you remember where the students could have used a telephone?
Because there wouldn't have been one in each room.
No, no.
I don't have any idea about that.
Let's see, typewriter.
Was a typewriter available to you at home?
I never did learn to write on one.
I never yet learned to write on one.
You said your father called you when he was called to take the job at OU.
How did he and the University of Oklahoma become linked?
Do you know?
No, I don't know that.
The Board of Regents, I guess, just... Because as far as I know, his work at A&M was very, very, very positive, and everybody was deeply proud to have him.
Well, I think it was, you know, it was kind of a hard decision.
Anytime you're going to make a change like that.
But he...
Had many good years at OU, too.
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Let's see.
Another name of a person.
Do you remember a man who had been an A&M director, later they'd call regent, from Houston named E.H. Cushing?
Mm-hmm.
That name's familiar, Cushing.
Do you remember anything?
But I don't know anything about him.
Well, when the old main building burned and the first dining hall burned...
A&M was bankrupt, and he wrote a check, a personal check, to keep the institution going until the legislature could meet in regular session and appropriate money.
And a previous A&M president named David Franklin Houston, or Houston, it's sometimes pronounced both ways, who later was also the UT president and who later was in President Wilson's cabinet,
he tried to persuade the legislature to close A&M down and move everything to Austin and merge it into the University of Texas.
And Mr. Cushing saved A&M.
Let's see, was there a bonfire at A&M in those days?
Oh, sure.
And you know, every year to this day, on certain night, my son from Enid calls me
Mom, tonight is the night of the bonfire, and it's going to be on television, and I turn it on and watch it every time.
Where was the bonfire held in those days?
I don't know what part of the campus it was on, but it was a big thing, and afterwards the whole student body came over to our house and got around the front porch.
What did they put in the bonfire?
everything, I guess, boxes, and now, goodness, I don't know what they do.
Now it's logs only.
Is that right?
But then, and what did, in those days, did they have anything they put on top of it?
Not that I remember.
Because a few years later, they would borrow someone's privy, paint it orange, and put it up there, and then...
they would raise the money to go to the family from which the privy had been stolen and pay for a new outhouse.
That's the old lag of spirit.
There you go.
There you go.
Let's see.
For you as a student, a full-time student, did you feel any pressure, personal pressure to...
be sure that you made your grades, that you behaved in a special way?
No.
You didn't?
No.
I was not aware of it.
Do you remember any students getting into trouble?
If so, what kind of punishment did they get from A&M then?
If it was bad enough, they got expelled, but I don't know.
Some kind of military thing, I suppose.
Now, as I looked at the photographs of your father, it looked like that quite often he had on a white suit.
Did he sometimes wear?
Oh, in the summer, I don't remember having a white suit much.
Back in those days, maybe he did.
I don't remember.
Oh, where was his office?
What building?
I assumed it was in the administration building.
And did you sometimes go over there?
Not much that I remember.
Did he have a secretary that was a special staff member for a long time?
I'm the only one I can think of that was one that owe you for all those years.
I don't, I just don't, oh let's see, I believe his name was Bailey.
Who?
S.G. Bailey.
S.G. Bailey.
That name kind of comes to me.
I've heard of that name.
Well, I told the children, and this is maybe getting off that subject, but I told the children that I was going to tell you about how I caught my husband.
Sure.
Yes.
Sure.
Well, we had gotten to Norman.
I had to cross over to Norman just a little bit.
And my husband, I guess Daddy was...
First year law.
Did I have two years of law school after that?
1925, he would have been probably a second year law student.
I thought he was president of the student council.
Well, he was.
He was.
But he, I think, I was thinking maybe two years anyway, he had gotten his same degree in 25 that I had.

but and he was in first year of law but he was also president of the student body so he worked closely with my father you know on student affairs and things and he just thought that since they kind of had a liking for each other they admired each other that it would be nice if he
would make a date with his daughter, just pure courtesy date, not because he wanted to.
So he called and asked me to go to a baseball game with him.
And I said I was delighted to go with him.
And so we went to the game and enjoyed the game.
And when the game was over, he looked around at me
He said, you are the first girl I've ever taken to a sporting event that would stay during the whole game.
And I said, at A&M, we don't do that.
We stay at the whole till the game is over.
And he was so impressed with that, I said, that's how I caught my husband.
So you're saying that it was the Aggie spirit?
It was the Aggie spirit that kept me at that ball game.
All right, that reminds me to ask, describe going to an A&M football game.
Oh, that was always a great event.
We had so many good football teams.
Was it called Kyle Field then?
Uh-huh, yeah.
When they built that stadium it was Kyle Field.
What did you and your friends do at a football game?
Just what everybody else did.
Just yell and of course the students all kind of stayed together.
Did you stand up the whole game?
We didn't do that then.
That's what they do now, but they didn't do that back in those days.
Did the Aggies kiss their dates after a touchdown?
Probably.
I don't remember that.
Because that's a strong tradition now.
That is, yeah.
And was there a formal march-in ceremony?
Well, at the half, they always had the whole student body come down and make a big T right down the middle of it.
Did you, as a coed, did you go down with them ever?
No, no.
Only?
No girls.
No girls?
No girls down there.
And you know, I've been real excited about our band.
It's now up to 405 members.
Well, it is a wonderful man.
It really is.
And as I said, the children have always kind of teased me about the way I make on, so about A&M.
And one of the games that they had down at OU, I started to say this about my son and Enid Lee Jr.,
was in the press box.

And at the half, of course they bring in all these other sports now, but at the football game, our band, the A&M band, was there and performed down the, you know, that precision marching, and the music was, you know, how it is.
And he called me from the press box.
And he said, I will have to admit that that is the finest band I think I have ever seen or something like that.
He said that A&M band is spectacular.
And he, from the press box, called me to tell him.
So I've been very proud of that because it is, I just think, a superb band.
Did you go to basketball and baseball games?
Oh, yeah.
And where were the baseballs?
Do you remember where they were played?
It's too far back for me to remember that.
I never have been as much of a baseball fan as I have basketball and football, mainly football.
But I always went to them when we were down there.
Was silver taps a tradition then?
When a student died, a special ceremony to
to commemorate that student's death.
Silver taps, I don't recall that.
Today, just west of the academic building, is the statue of Lawrence Sullivan Ross.
Sol Ross, yeah.
And then the buglers from the band come out on the second floor of the building, and the students gather in silence, all the student body around that,

and there is a ceremony, and then they play taps, and you are then to go back to your room in total silence and not supposed to turn on your lights unless you really have to study, and if so, close the blinds and close your door to silently try to remember your friendship for that student that is gone.
Well, for goodness sakes, isn't that interesting?
Let's see, celebrity visitors.
Do you remember any famous people coming to visit?
Oh, I'm sure there were plenty of them, but I don't, I just can't remember those.
I don't think, I don't know of President Woodrow Wilson coming or McKendree.
I don't believe so, and I don't remember that.
Let me see, I was going to...
Oh, Sol Ross, when you said Sol Ross, in the old campus that I'm, that's all that I knew about, and had a statue of him.
Yes, ma'am.
Is that statue still there?
Oh, yes.
Still there?
Every freshman is supposed to polish it at least once.
Well, but when I was down there, if it rained, some freshman had to hold an umbrella over his head the whole time.
I mean, you said, Saul Ross, that's the first thing I ever think of.
That's great.
Let's see.
How much did things cost?
Do you remember the prices of things?
A dress?
Not like it does now, but I don't know.
What about that haircut that you got in Houston?
Do you remember what your mother paid that beautician?
No.
I just know she turned down the $25.
While you were living in College Station, did you and your family make any vacation trips that you recall?
But most of the time, our vacation was going to either Chicago to the University of Chicago.
My father was taking classes to get a degree there.
And then we went for several summers to New York with him while he was going to Columbia.
So those were our vacation trips like that.
Now, did he get a degree while he was at A&M?
Did he complete?
A degree at one of those schools?
No, he'd gotten his degree at Baylor.
And then the next was, I guess it was, what was his law degree at the University of Chicago?
He got one graduate degree at the University of Chicago and one at Columbia, but I don't know which one was which.
Ph.D. was from Columbia, I think.
Ph.D. was from Columbia.
In what specialty?
Sociology, wasn't it?
Well, that was his field, but.
I'm not sure that I ever saw that.
And he was chosen.
I've got a little medal upstairs.
He was chosen outstanding graduate one year.
If I could chat with your father today, what do you think he would remember most fondly about A&M?
But I think he would have a lot of the same spirit himself, because I think they really enjoyed the years down there.
Was it easy to move away, for you, to move from College Station?
Well, fortunately it was in the summertime.
And I graduated that spring, and then we came right up to Norman.
And did you meet, and you met that young man the next spring, that special?
That was, well, that was just, that fall I met him.
Oh, that fall, oh.
Yeah.
That's very good, good timing for him.
Let's see, we're getting near the completion.
What effects did?
those years at College Station, what effects did those have on your life and the kind of person you have become?
They had a lot of effects on my life because I look back on them as still some of the best years.
And I've had a wonderful life from beginning to end.
I've just never known anybody so fortunate.
I was trying to think of some of the things that I... Did it affect your set of values, your attitudes about people?
No, I think I've stayed about the same.
Children might have an answer to that.
Let's see.
All right.
Next to the last question.
Let's make believe that someone gives you a million dollar check with only one

requirement you must give it to texas a m but you can decide what they are to do with it what would you tell if you could give a m a million dollars what would what would you want them to do with it send the girls home send the girls home yeah it's not it's not quite it's not the same now that it
But now that wouldn't cost any money, though.
What would?
Oh, to spend money on it.
Well, just make a bigger and better college.
Then the last question.
What are your feelings about Texas A&M today?
Same they've always been.
I just loved at Texas A&M.
It was a real special time for me.
And there was anything I accomplished or did that would help you in what you're doing.
